NYC Motor and Vehicle Car Collisions

Glenda Ascencio

November 17 2015

Introduction: This research is about investigating the causes, seasons, locations, years and months where there are more car collisions in New York City. We obtained our data from the Motor Vehicle Collisions in New York City provided by the Police Department (NYPD) which had detailed information of more than 665,000 of reported car collisions in NYC.

Dataset: The variables have information about the boroughs, locations, street names, total people injured, total people killed, total pedestrians injured, total pedestrians killed, total cyclist injured, total cyclist killed, total motorist injured, total motorist killed, reason vehicles crashed, and type of vehicle. All this data was imported, cleaned, and vizualized into R and saved as car_collision for easier analyzation in the future.

  1. First of all, we are trying to find the seasons with the highest number of car collisions. According to our results, Brooklyn has the highest number of car collisions on May 05, 2015 with 4507 compared to the other seasons less than 4300 and the other boroughs which had less than 3850 number of car collisions. In Brooklyn, after we filtered the data so we could obtain the numbers of car collision greater than 4200 for each season, we were able to observe that the season with the highest number of car collision is the Spring 2015 with 17354, the summer with 12857, the fall with 4221, and the winter with the lowest number of car collisions (less than 4200). Spring: march-may summer: june-August Autumn: September-November Winter: December-February
  # a) Searching for answer
seasons <- car_collision %>%
  group_by(borough, season, year_month) %>%
  summarize(season_collision=n())
  
  # b) Filtering in order to obtain the highest car collisions above 4200
seasons1 <- filter(seasons, season_collision >= 4200)

  1. Since we saw that the Spring has the highest number of car collision, we tried to investigate if the Daylight Saving Time caused more car collisions in NYC. We know that the DST changes do not necessarily occur on the same date every year. For instance, on March the clock is turned one hour forward and on November the clock is turned one hour backward. Therefore, we procedeed to investigate the years from 2012 to 2015, comparing the number of crashes on the Monday after the shift from Daylight Saving Time to Standard time and the previous Monday, allowing us to compare Monday to Monday with the only variable being the time shift.
daylight_saving <- car_collision %>%
  group_by(date, season, borough) %>%
  summarize(dls=n())  
  
    # a) We didn't had the March 11 DST in information in 2012. That is why we just proceded in analyzing Monday November 05 after the shift from Daylight Saving Time to Standard time and compare it to the previous Monday October 29, 2015. Our results shows that for each borough there was a huge number of increasement after the daylight saving.

  1. Most of the time, the Daylight Saving Time on November increased the number of car collisions. Therefore, we decided to further investigate the reasons why most of the car accidents occured in NYC. Our results demonstrated that on Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens, and the Bronx we have the highest number of car collision due to driving inattention. According to the Advances in Research by professor Michael Regan he said that 71% of the crashes occured, 46% of the crashes-near, and 60% of the SCEs were caused in non-driving task just before the occurance of the kinematics trigger. 77% occured by texting where the driver’s eyes were off the forward roadway which caused cognitive distration. My results proves his point by showing all higher causes of car collisions.
  # a) Calculations
reasons_type <- car_collision %>% 
  group_by(borough, year_month, season, reason_vehicle1_crashed) %>% 
  summarize(reasons = n())

  # b) Arranging the data so I can obtain the high reasons that caused car collisions. We know that for each reason 631 is the max number of car collisions. Therefore, in order to find the top 5 reasons I will filter the data 
reasons_type <- filter(reasons_type, reason_vehicle1_crashed != "Unspecified")
reasons_type <- filter(reasons_type, reasons >= 220)

  # c) Plot the highest causes of car collisions for each borough
ggplot(reasons_type, aes(x = reason_vehicle1_crashed, y = reasons, color = as.factor(season)))+
  geom_point(aes(shape = as.factor(season), size = 2))+
  ggtitle("Reasons That Most Car Accidents Occured")+
  xlab("Reasons They That They Were Killed")+
  ylab("Total Number of invididuals killed")+
  facet_wrap(~ borough)+
  scale_y_continuous(limits=c(220, 550))+
  theme(legend.title=element_blank(),
        axis.text.x=element_text(angle=80, hjust=1),
        legend.background = element_rect(fill = "transparent"))

    # d) Plotting the highest reason for the number of car collision

  1. Finally, we also like to have an estimation about in how many minutes we have a car accidents in NYC so we can educate other to drive carefully in order to reduce the number of car collisions. Our results showed that in every two minutes and 4 second there is a car accident in NYC.
recent_year <- car_collision$DateTime[1]
old_year <- car_collision$DateTime[nrow(car_collision)]
diff_seconds <- as.numeric(recent_year) - as.numeric(old_year) 
diff_seconds #Rll = 94607400
## numeric(0)
diff_seconds / (60*60*24)   #Rll = 1094.02 
## numeric(0)
#1094 days have passed. There are 614,437 accidents in total. 
accidents_per_minute <- 614437/1094
accidents_per_minute #Rll = 561.6. That's means that every 2.4 minutes there's an accident
## [1] 561.6426

In conclusion, every two minutes and four second there is a car accident in NYC. Millions of individuals ages from 1 to 90 are being killed in each borough due to driving inattention (dictraction due the use of cellphones, putting make up), failure to yield right of way, fatigue, and driving in a drunk condition. Many of these accidents occur during the workday or during the commute to and from work/home. The only way we can reduce the number of car collision is to implement educational workshops about car collisions on high school, college, hospital, churches, and in NYC transit system educating parents, employers, and adolescents on how to drive carefully, how to have an effective driving training, how much the cost of motor vehicle crashes cost, how to have best safe driving practices, and help families and employes overcome tragedy.
